    <section class="content right-sidebar">
   		 	
   		 							
					    		
	    			<h2 class="page-title">Making the Most of Your Closet Space</h2>
	    		
	    			    	
	    	
	    	<div class="ln-single-meta">
	    		23 April 2013  in   
	    		<span class="ln-post-categories"><a href="http://sweetlemonmag.com/category/fashion/" title="View all posts in Fashion" rel="category tag">Fashion</a></span>
	    		| <a href="http://sweetlemonmag.com/fashion/making-the-most-of-your-closet-space/#comments">No Comments</a>
	    	</div>

		

		    	
					
					<div class="ln-single-content">
						<p>As any big city dweller knows, living space is at a premium. You pay twice as much for a space half (or more!) the size of your friends’ places in the ‘burbs. Guest bedroom? Think again. Your visiting friends and family kick it on the couch out in the living room. Dining room table? No way. That’s for people who don’t eat 96% of their meals out of a plastic to-go container anyway.  And a closet actually fit for adult-sized clothes? Dream on, sister. You’ll be lucky if you can fit a rolling rack between your bed and the Ikea shelf crammed full of artfully arranged living essentials.</p>
<p>When I first signed a lease on my apartment in New York City, I, quite truthfully, panicked. Not because I was moving hundreds of miles away from all my friends and family. Not because I’d be starting a new job. Not even because I’d have to figure out the layout of a new grocery store. I panicked because my closet was more than half the size of my previous apartment. As someone who may just be a borderline, TLC approved (clothing) hoarder, I panicked. Could it fit? Would it fit? Should I consider calling an interventionist?</p>
<p>Luckily, I didn’t have to go that far. Instead, I called up my friend Jessica of <a href="http://www.mystylevita.com/" target="_blank">My Style Vita </a>fame. Jessica, an Atlanta-area fashion blogger and style aficionado, offers a bevy of services for the fashion conscious consumer. Wardrobe Consulting? Virtual Styling? She does it all! In fact, she’ll even help you shop. As in, you don’t have to worry about parking your car, successfully avoiding the Miss Annie’s pretzel booth in the food court, or pretending you don’t hear the salesman chasing you through the atrium offering you a free sample of Dead Sea hand lotion &#8211; she’ll do it <i>all</i> for you! JACKPOT. So, with all this in mind, I knew she’d be just the gal to help me get over my fashion &#8211; and spatially challenged &#8211; hump.</p>
<p>I went to Jessica with one question: how can I edit down my wardrobe to fit in my new space without sacrificing any style? I was especially concerned about how, with only a few pieces, I could dress for whatever life in New York City threw my way. What should I bring? What should I leave? What should I invest in? Jessica, of course, had all the stylish answers. Presto! Problem solved. Here’s what she said:</p>
<p>When it comes to teeny, tiny Manhattan apartments, or even monster-sized, swoon-worthy closets, there are three tips you should live by.</p>
<p><strong>First Tip: </strong>Spend some time trying everything on in your closet. Yes, <i>everything</i>. Try it <i>all</i> - play dress up, put on some Britney Spears, and get to trying on. If it has a hole, stain, or doesn&#8217;t fit right at all &#8211; get rid of it. Seriously toss it and don&#8217;t think twice, you&#8217;ll thank me later. If it can easily be tailored to be amazing, then put it aside and go get it tailored. But, actually <i>get</i> it tailored &#8211; don’t just put it back in your closet!</p>
<p><a class="no-eff img-link lightbox" href="http://sweetlemonmag.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/jessicaforslm.png"><img class="alignnone  wp-image-3658" alt="jessicaforslm" src="http://sweetlemonmag.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/jessicaforslm.png" width="620" /></a></p>
<p><strong>Second Tip: </strong>Identify your favorite transitional pieces. Those favorite pieces that’ll help you go from day to night &#8211; like my moto jacket that I wear with <i>everything</i> (see photographs above). It can turn a spring dress that you wore out all day to go flea market shopping into a much edgier look for the evening. The same goes for work clothes. You need pretty blouses for work, but be sure to find tops that work nicely for night time, too &#8211; garments that may only need a few pieces of jewelry to transition.  Now, on to jeans, these are, hands down, my favorite transitional piece. When done right, they can go from the office to night to weekend to cocktail party. So, invest in good fitting, dark washed jeans, a pair or two of skinnies, and definitely a nice wide leg trouser. You just can&#8217;t go wrong with a good wide leg trouser!</p>
<p><strong>Third Tip: </strong>For those pieces you think you&#8217;re going to wear, I&#8217;ve got a challenge for you &#8211; flip all of your hangers around. All of them. When you take something out, and then put it back in your closet after wear or laundering, put the hanger back the normal way. The hangers will tell you what you are and aren&#8217;t wearing, and it will make cleaning out your closet the next time that much easier.</p>
<p>I hope, with these three tips, your teeny tiny closet becomes a sanctuary for you to get dressed in every morning. I have full faith in your ability to toss, keep, and tailor. Happy organizing!</p>
<p>By <a href="http://www.twitter.com/lmhughes" target="_blank">Lauren M. Hughes</a>, with <a href="http://www.twitter.com/mystylevita" target="_blank">Jessica</a> of <a href="http://www.mystylevita.com/" target="_blank">My Style Vita</a>.</p>
<p>Photography by <a href="http://www.rebekahcarsonphotography.com/" target="_blank">Rebekah Carson Photography</a>, for Sweet Lemon Mag.</p>
